# Exercise 1 – Implementing the Singleton Pattern

## Objective

The objective of this exercise is to understand and implement the Singleton Design Pattern. The Singleton Pattern ensures that a class has only one instance throughout the application's lifecycle and provides a global access point to that instance.

## What is the Singleton Design Pattern?

The Singleton Pattern is a creational design pattern that restricts the instantiation of a class to a single object. It is commonly used when exactly one object is required to coordinate actions across the system.

## Features of Singleton Pattern

* Only one instance of the class is created.
* Provides a global access point to the instance.
* Prevents multiple object creation.
* Constructor is declared private.
* Instance is created using a static method.

## Implementation Steps

1. Declare a private static instance of the class.
2. Make the constructor private to prevent external object creation.
3. Provide a public static `getInstance()` method to return the single instance.
4. Create the instance only if it does not already exist.

## Advantages

* Saves memory by avoiding unnecessary object creation.
* Ensures consistency across the application.
* Provides controlled access to shared resources.
* Easy to implement and widely used.

## Disadvantages

* Global state can make testing more difficult.
* Can introduce tight coupling if overused.
* Requires additional synchronization in multithreaded environments.

## Applications of Singleton Pattern

* Logging systems
* Configuration management
* Database connections
* Cache management
* Thread pools

## Time Complexity

| Operation     | Complexity |
| ------------- | ---------- |
| getInstance() | O(1)       |
| log()         | O(1)       |

## Learning Outcomes

* Understood the Singleton Design Pattern.
* Learned how to restrict object creation.
* Implemented a singleton Logger class.
* Verified that only one object exists throughout the application.
